  "prompt": "What schools can I apply for with a GRE score of Q-165 V-153?",
  "response": "With a GRE score of 165 in the Quantitative section and 153 in the Verbal section, you have a competitive score primarily for quantitative-focused programs, such as those in the fields of engineering, mathematics, computer science, and some quantitative social sciences. Here are some general guidelines and types of schools you might consider:\n\n### Highly Competitive Programs\n- **Top-Tier Schools:** Many top universities (e.g., MIT, Stanford, UC Berkeley) may still consider your application but might expect higher overall scores, particularly in Verbal, depending on the program.\n\n### Competitive Programs\n- **Mid to Upper Tier Schools:** Many programs at schools like University of Michigan, University of California San Diego, and Georgia Tech may find your quantitative score impressive, especially for STEM-oriented programs.\n\n### Moderate Programs\n- **Solid Programs:** Schools like University of Florida, University of Wisconsin-Madison, and University of Maryland may be good targets, depending on their specific average GRE scores for admitted students.\n\n### List of Specific Programs to Consider\n1. **STEM Programs:**\n   - University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign\n   - Purdue University\n   - University of Texas at Austin\n   - University of Washington\n\n2. **Social Sciences/Business:**\n   - University of Michigan - Ann Arbor (for certain social science programs)\n   - Boston University\n   - Texas A&M University (for specific programs linked to engineering and management)\n\n### Factors to Consider\n- **Program Focus:** Certain programs may weigh the quantitative score more heavily (e.g., engineering), while others may also consider your verbal score significantly (e.g., psychology, humanities).\n- **Other Application Components:** Consider the entire application package, including your GPA, letters of recommendation, statement of purpose, and relevant experience. A strong overall application can compensate for a lower GRE verbal score.\n- **Research the School's Requirements:** Check the specific requirements and average scores for your target programs on their official websites, as they vary by department.\n\n### Conclusion\nWith your scores, you have a good chance at many solid programs, particularly in quantitative fields. It's wise to apply to a mix of schools, including those where you meet or exceed the average GRE scores and a few where your application strengths can shine despite score discrepancies.",
